    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1974-08-16T15:55:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1974-08-16T15:15:00-05:00" n="23"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d23">
                <head>23. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d23fn1"
                        >Source: National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 59, Lot File
                        91D414, Records of <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Henry Kissinger</persName>,
                        Box 9, <gloss target="#t_Nodis_1">Nodis</gloss> Memcons, Aug. 1974, Folder
                        4. Secret; <gloss target="#t_Nodis_1">Nodis</gloss>. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_RPW_1">Rodman</persName>. The meeting was held in the
                        Secretary’s office at the Department of State.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1974-08-16T16:15:00-04:00" to="1974-08-16T16:55:00-04:00"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date">August 16, 1974, 4:15–4:55
                            p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DS_1">Simcha Dinitz</persName>, Ambassador of
                        Israel</item>
                    <item>Mordechai Shalev, Minister, Embassy of Israel</item>
                    <item>Dr. <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>, Secretary
                        of State and Assistant to the President for National Security Affairs</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RPW_1">Peter W. Rodman</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Staff</item>
                </list>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_DS_1">Dinitz</persName>: I have some regards indirectly
                    from the Senators who met with you yesterday [on the <persName
                        corresp="#p_JHM_1">Jackson</persName> Amendment].<note n="2" xml:id="d23fn2"
                        >Brackets in the original. <persName corresp="#p_DS_1">Dinitz</persName> is
                        referring to the August 15 meeting; see <ref target="#d16">Document
                        16</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: Yeah, but we can’t do what
                    they want.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_DS_1">Dinitz</persName>: They said only one sentence is a
                    problem.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: The letter is all right, but
                    the Soviets can’t possibly live up to that interpretive statement. We have
                    assurances that the harassment will stop, that <persName corresp="#p_BLI_1"
                        >Brezhnev</persName> will make himself personally responsible. The
                    interpretive statement can be a statement of objectives, but not as a detailed
                    commitment.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_DS_1">Dinitz</persName>: I think they came towards
                    you.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: How?</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_DS_1">Dinitz</persName>: They made it a monitoring
                    amendment.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: Yes, but it can’t be
                    something they will harass us with a year from now. Would you accept it if you
                    were a sovereign government?</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_DS_1">Dinitz</persName>: I don’t harass people, that is
                    the first thing. But if it is a new turn in relations . . .</p>
                <pb facs="0093" n="62" xml:id="pg_62"/>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: But if they stop harassment,
                    it will show in the numbers. If they don’t want to do it, you can’t solve it
                    with a document. I am assuming there is a power struggle there, just like here.
                    Look at <persName corresp="#p_SJR_1">Schlesinger</persName>: one day he is to
                    the right of me, one day he is to the left! We will accept the letter. We will
                    ask for a revision of the interpretive statement or we will use it as
                    guidelines. We will want it for the President to have discretionary power
                    subject to Congressional veto, not to have to ask for it every year.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_DS_1">Dinitz</persName>: I know <persName
                        corresp="#p_JHM_1">Jackson</persName> is anxious to compromise.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: <persName corresp="#p_JHM_1"
                        >Jackson</persName>’s press conference was unhelpful.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_DS_1">Dinitz</persName>: Unhelpful?</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: It was helpful in giving the
                    President the credit; that was a good face-saving thing. But it was unhelpful in
                    relations with the Soviet Union.<note n="3" xml:id="d23fn3">During a meeting in
                        the Oval Office on August 17, <persName corresp="#p_FGR_1">Ford</persName>
                        and <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName> discussed the Trade
                        Bill, Soviet emigration, and U.S.-Israeli relations: “President: I’m glad
                        Scoop moved. <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: We called
                        him yesterday and he was conciliatory. You might consider talking to him
                        again next week. I told <persName corresp="#p_DS_1">Dinitz</persName> he had
                        to help us here and that <persName corresp="#p_RY_1">Rabin</persName> had to
                        come in early September. President: We have to give Scoop his amendment.
                            <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: If you get waiver
                        authority, that Congress would have to veto, it’s okay. President: What he
                        wants is his amendment. The supporters don’t understand the waiver
                        authority. <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>: The Soviet
                        Union won’t buy going in every year for legislation. They will complain
                        about this, but will go along with it. A Member of Congress last night said
                        they want a compromise. President: If we can pull it off and get the bill,
                        it is the best thing we can do.” (Ford Library, National Security Adviser,
                        Memoranda of Conversations, 1973–1977, Box 5)</note>
                </p>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion of the Middle East and U.S.-Israeli relations.]</p>
            </div>
